english:
  title: In Response to Scholar Lee Ji-sim's Inscription Left at the Guest House in Seondeok Station
  author: Lim Yu-jung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The setting sun, the flowing water—east and west they go,
    yet shallow and deep, the mountains' hues remain the same through ages.
    Ten years of memory fly away like birds in flight,
    while ten thousand leagues of clear river mirror the azure sky.
    The tavern hides within the flower's tender shade,
    and one who leans upon the railing stands amid the moonlight.
    I wish to repay this lovely scene with measured verse,
    yet ashamed, my words fall short—my meaning still unrefined.
  footnotes:
    - This poem is a collaborative work in the Korean poetic tradition, where each couplet is attributed to a classical Chinese poet or literary figure, creating a dialogue across time and space.
    - The imagery of the guest house, tavern, and moonlit railing evokes the transient nature of travel and human connection—themes central to Korean literary gatherings of this period.
